Eles podem usar o código acima para adicionar tags, precisando apenas definir corretamente o local para adicionar no DOM.

Podemos mostrar como reutilizar o corpo de uma requisição `menusDish` existente. No console do DevTools, usar algo assim:

```javascript
const original = {
  operationName: "menusDish",
  variables: { id: 18998849 },
  query: `query menusDish($id: ID!) { ... }`
};

async function fetchMods(menuItemId) {
  const body = {...original, variables: {...original.variables, id: menuItemId}};
  ...
}
```

No entanto, a dúvida é se `menusDish` usa `dishId` ou `menuItemId`. A resposta que você recebeu não é o payload da requisição, mas sim a resposta. É necessário verificar a requisição no DevTools. O melhor é usar a opção "Copy as fetch" do Chrome para copiar a requisição inteira e adaptá-la ao código, removendo apenas os bits dinâmicos, como o ID.

parts:
Yes, this is 100% possible with a DevTools script. 🙂  
You can:

1. **Grab each row (card) from the DOM.**
2. **Get its `data-lazy-item-id` (menu item ID).**
3. **Call the `menusDish` GraphQL operation with that ID.**
4. **Inject tags into each row with the modifier info you care about.**

You’d run this in the **Console** (or save it as a DevTools “Snippet”).

---

## 1. Basic idea

From your HTML:

```html
<div
  class="MuiCard-root-2131 ..."
  data-lazy-item-id="30236836"
  data-cy="menu_item_card"
>
  ...
</div>
```

So for each `[data-cy="menu_item_card"]` you can:

- Read `data-lazy-item-id` → `30236836`
- Call `/graphql` with `menusDish` for that ID.
- Get `data.dish.selectedMenuItem.modifierGroups`.
- Create a small `<div>` and append it into the card to show tags like:

> omelette add ons · omelette exclusions · breakfast choice · omelette toast

---

## 2. Example DevTools script (template)

Paste this into the **Console** on that page.

You’ll need to **fill in the GraphQL `query` and the correct variable name** from the real `menusDish` request in the Network tab (I’ll mark that part):

```js
(async () => {
  // 1) Grab all item cards on the page
  const cards = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('[data-cy="menu_item_card"]'));
  if (!cards.length) {
    console.warn('No menu item cards found.');
    return;
  }

  // 2) Base GraphQL body — ADAPT this to match the real menusDish request
  const baseBody = {
    operationName: 'menusDish',
    // 👇 copy this from the real request in Network → Payload
    query: `PASTE_MENUSDISH_QUERY_HERE`,
    variables: {
      // 👇 change this key to whatever the real request uses:
      // e.g. { menuItemId: 30236836 } OR { id: 18998849 } etc.
      menuItemId: 0
    }
    // If the real request has an "extensions" field, you can also copy it:
    // extensions: { ... }
  };

  async function fetchModifiers(menuItemId) {
    const body = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(baseBody));
    body.variables.menuItemId = Number(menuItemId); // or dishId, etc.

    const res = await fetch('/graphql', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify(body)
    });

    const json = await res.json();
    const groups = json?.data?.dish?.selectedMenuItem?.modifierGroups || [];
    return groups;
  }

  for (const card of cards) {
    const menuItemId = card.getAttribute('data-lazy-item-id');
    if (!menuItemId) continue;

    // 3) Create a placeholder tag container in the row
    const tagBar = document.createElement('div');
    tagBar.textContent = 'Loading modifiers…';
    tagBar.style.fontSize = '12px';
    tagBar.style.color = '#555';
    tagBar.style.marginTop = '4px';

    // You can adjust where this goes; this puts it under the name/description:
    const headerContent =
      card.querySelector('[class*="CardHeader-content"]') || card;
    headerContent.appendChild(tagBar);

    // 4) Fetch modifier groups and update the tags
    try {
      const groups = await fetchModifiers(menuItemId);
      if (!groups.length) {
        tagBar.textContent = 'No modifiers';
      } else {
        // Example: show just group names
        tagBar.textContent = groups.map(g => g.name).join(' · ');

        // Or if you want more detailed info, you could do:
        // tagBar.textContent = groups
        //   .map(g => `${g.name}: ${g.modifiers.map(m => m.name).join(', ')}`)
        //   .join(' | ');
      }
    } catch (e) {
      console.error('Error fetching modifiers for', menuItemId, e);
      tagBar.textContent = 'Error loading modifiers';
    }
  }
})();
```

### What you have to customize

1. In DevTools → Network → find a **real `menusDish` request**, open the Payload:
   - Copy the **`query`** string and paste it in `query: \`...\``.
   - Note the **variables shape**. If it’s:
     - `variables: { menuItemId: 30236836 }` → keep `menuItemId`.
     - `variables: { id: 18998849 }` → change the script to use `variables.id` etc.

2. (If present) copy `extensions` from the request and add to `baseBody`.

Once that’s set, the script will:

- Loop through all cards in the “Three Egg Omelettes” section.
- Inject a line of text under each item name/description listing the modifier groups.

---

## 3. Limitations and next steps

- **DevTools script is temporary**: you’ll need to re-run it after each page reload.
- For your team, the polished version would be:
  - A **Tampermonkey userscript** doing the same thing automatically, or
  - A **Chrome extension** with this logic in a content script.

But for prototyping and for your own workflow, **yes**, DevTools is enough to inject those tags exactly where you showed in the screenshot.

