parts:
Yep, your idea absolutely works 👌

From that HTML you pasted we *already* have the `menuItemId` for each row, and it matches the `selectedMenuItem.id` in the `menusDish` response.

Example for ABC Omelette:

- In the DOM:
  - `data-lazy-item-id="30236836"`
  - `id="30236836-menu-item"`
- In the `menusDish` response:
  - `"selectedMenuItem": { ..., "id": 30236836, ... }`

So you can:

1. Grab the `menuItemId` from the HTML.
2. Use it in a GraphQL request.
3. Inject your tags into each card.

---

### 1. Getting the `menuItemId` from the page

In the DevTools console while you’re on that Menus page:

```js
// All menu item cards in the section
const cards = document.querySelectorAll('[data-cy="menu_item_card"]');

cards.forEach(card => {
  const menuItemId = card.getAttribute('data-lazy-item-id'); // e.g. "30236836"
  const title = card.querySelector('.MuiTypography-h4-467')?.textContent.trim();
  console.log(menuItemId, title);
});
```

That should log something like:

```text
30236836 "ABC Omelette"
30236856 "Denver Omelette"
30236870 "Garlic Chicken Omelette"
...
```

That `menuItemId` is exactly the one you see in the JSON (`selectedMenuItem.id`).

---

### 2. Using that ID in GraphQL

You already have a working `menusDish` request from Network. Reuse **the same** body, just change the variables.

Rough sketch (you’ll need to plug in the real `operationName`, `extensions.operationId`, and whatever variable name you see in the original request):

```js
async function fetchDishByMenuItemId(menuItemId) {
  const body = {
    operationName: "menusDish",              // from Network tab
    variables: {
      // ⚠️ This part must match the real request:
      // If the original uses `menuItemId`, use that.
      // If it uses `dishId`, this won't work directly and we'll need a mapping.
      menuItemId: Number(menuItemId),
      restaurantId: 95845                   // your rest ID
    },
    extensions: {
      operationId: "PopmenuClient/xxxxxxxx" // copy from Network
    }
    // If the original request has a `query` field, include it too.
  };

  const res = await fetch("/graphql", {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "content-type": "application/json" },
    credentials: "include", // keep your session
    body: JSON.stringify(body)
  });

  const json = await res.json();
  return json.data.dish; // same shape as the response you pasted
}
```

If the schema doesn’t actually accept `menuItemId` on that query and only uses `dishId`, no worries: you still have a unique way to tie DOM → data:

- DOM gives you `menuItemId` (e.g. `30236836`).
- The `menusDish` response includes both:
  - `selectedMenuItem.id` (menu item ID)
  - `selectedMenuItem.dishId` (dish ID)

So worst case, you can write a **custom** GraphQL query that takes a `menuItemId` and returns `dishId` + `modifierGroups` for that menu item. Since you’re running in the browser on `my.popmenu.com`, you can send your own GraphQL `query` string in the body even if the UI never uses that exact operation.

---

### 3. Injecting tags into each row

Once you have the dish data for an item, you can build some tag text from the modifier groups and stick it into the blank space of the row.

Example:

```js
function addTagsToCard(card, dish) {
  const tagContainer = document.createElement('div');
  tagContainer.style.fontSize = '11px';
  tagContainer.style.opacity = '0.7';
  tagContainer.style.marginTop = '4px';

  const groupNames = dish.selectedMenuItem.modifierGroups
    .map(g => g.name)
    .join(' • ');

  tagContainer.textContent = groupNames;

  const content = card.querySelector('.MuiCardHeader-content-2135');
  content?.appendChild(tagContainer);
}
```

Then glue it together:

```js
(async () => {
  const cards = document.querySelectorAll('[data-cy="menu_item_card"]');

  for (const card of cards) {
    const menuItemId = card.getAttribute('data-lazy-item-id');
    const dish = await fetchDishByMenuItemId(menuItemId);
    addTagsToCard(card, dish);
  }
})();
```

You’ll probably refine:

- How you summarize modifiers into tags.
- How you style them (little pill chips instead of plain text).
- Maybe limit to a subset of groups (e.g. only “omelette toast”, “breakfast sides”, etc).

But structurally: **yes**, grabbing `menuItemId` from the DOM and using it is exactly the right approach.

Yep, you can totally automate it — no manual copying of IDs needed.  

The key things we’ve already got:

- Every card has the menu item id in the DOM:  
  - `id="30236836-menu-item"`  
  - `data-lazy-item-id="30236836"`
- You already know the GraphQL endpoint: `https://my.popmenu.com/graphql`
- When you click an item, the app calls the `menusDish` operation and returns the `dish` with `selectedMenuItem.modifierGroups`.

So a single DevTools script can:

1. Find all the menu item cards on the page.
2. Extract the `menuItemId` from each card.
3. Call the same `menusDish` GraphQL operation for each `menuItemId`.
4. Read the modifier groups from the response.
5. Inject your “modifier tags” into each card row.

---

## One-shot DevTools script (no manual IDs)

Paste this in the Console on the menu editor page (Three Egg Omelettes section visible).

You’ll need to tweak **only** the `variables` object to match the real `menusDish` request body from Network (I’ll show where).

```js
(async () => {
  // ---- CONFIG (edit this part to match your real request) ----
  const GRAPHQL_ENDPOINT = "/graphql";           // same origin, so we can use relative path
  const RESTAURANT_ID = 95845;                   // from your existing requests

  // Copy ONE working menusDish request from Network tab and look at its JSON body.
  // It will look something like:
  //
  // {
  //   "operationName": "menusDish",
  //   "variables": { "menuItemId": 30236836, "restaurantId": 95845 },
  //   "extensions": { "operationId": "PopmenuClient/...." }
  // }
  //
  // Take the operationName + extensions block and keep them here:
  const baseBody = {
    operationName: "menusDish",
    variables: {
      // we'll override menuItemId per card below
      menuItemId: null,
      restaurantId: RESTAURANT_ID
    },
    extensions: {
      operationId: "PopmenuClient/PUT-YOUR-REAL-OPERATION-ID-HERE"
    }
  };

  // If your real request uses another variable name (e.g. "dishId" or "id"),
  // change menuItemId above and in buildRequestBody() to match it.

  // ---- HELPER: build per-item GraphQL request body ----
  function buildRequestBody(menuItemId) {
    const body = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(baseBody)); // deep clone
    body.variables.menuItemId = menuItemId;            // or body.variables.dishId = ...
    return body;
  }

  // ---- HELPER: how to turn modifier groups into a short tag string ----
  function buildTagFromModifierGroups(groups) {
    if (!groups || !groups.length) return "No modifiers";

    // Example: show group names separated by •
    // You can make this smarter (initials, special icons, etc.)
    const names = groups.map(g => g.name).filter(Boolean);
    return names.join(" • ");
  }

  // ---- HELPER: inject the tag into the card UI ----
  function injectTagIntoCard(card, tagText) {
    const header = card.querySelector(".MuiCardHeader-content-2135");
    if (!header) return;

    // Avoid duplicates if you rerun the script
    let tag = header.querySelector(".__mod-tags");
    if (!tag) {
      tag = document.createElement("div");
      tag.className = "__mod-tags";
      tag.style.fontSize = "11px";
      tag.style.marginTop = "4px";
      tag.style.opacity = "0.75";
      tag.style.whiteSpace = "nowrap";
      tag.style.overflow = "hidden";
      tag.style.textOverflow = "ellipsis";
      header.appendChild(tag);
    }
    tag.textContent = tagText;
  }

  // ---- MAIN: loop over all cards, fetch modifiers, inject tags ----
  const cards = Array.from(
    document.querySelectorAll('[data-cy="menu_item_card"]')
  );

  console.log(`Found ${cards.length} menu items`);

  for (const card of cards) {
    // Get menuItemId from DOM (data-lazy-item-id is clean, or fall back to id="12345-menu-item")
    const rawId =
      card.getAttribute("data-lazy-item-id") ||
      (card.id || "").split("-")[0];

    const menuItemId = Number(rawId);
    if (!menuItemId) {
      console.warn("Could not parse menu item id for card", card);
      continue;
    }

    try {
      const res = await fetch(GRAPHQL_ENDPOINT, {
        method: "POST",
        headers: {
          "content-type": "application/json"
          // If your real request has extra headers (e.g. x-csrf-token),
          // copy them from Network and add them here.
        },
        body: JSON.stringify(buildRequestBody(menuItemId)),
        credentials: "include" // send your logged-in cookies
      });

      if (!res.ok) {
        console.warn("Request failed for item", menuItemId, res.status);
        continue;
      }

      const json = await res.json();
      const dish = json?.data?.dish;
      const selected = dish?.selectedMenuItem;

      const modifierGroups = selected?.modifierGroups || [];
      const tagText = buildTagFromModifierGroups(modifierGroups);

      injectTagIntoCard(card, tagText);
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("Error for item", menuItemId, err);
    }
  }

  console.log("Done tagging modifiers");
})();
```

---

### What you still need to do once

1. **Grab a real `menusDish` request body**  
   - Open DevTools → Network → XHR/fetch.  
   - Click an omelette row.  
   - Find the `menusDish` request → Payload tab.  
   - Copy:
     - `operationName` (likely `"menusDish"`)
     - `extensions.operationId` string
     - The **variable name** used for the menu item id (`menuItemId`, `dishId`, etc.).

2. **Update the script config**  
   - Put that `operationId` string into `baseBody.extensions.operationId`.  
   - If the variable name is not `menuItemId`, rename `menuItemId` everywhere in `baseBody` and `buildRequestBody()` to match.

After that, the script will:

- Automatically read every item id on the page,
- Call the Popmenu GraphQL API for each,
- Look at `selectedMenuItem.modifierGroups`,
- Inject whatever summary/tag you want into the blank part of the card.

If you want, next step we can:

- Tune `buildTagFromModifierGroups` to match your menu build rules (e.g. show only “add-ons / exclusions / sides / toast” as tiny labeled pills).
- Turn this console script into a small Chrome extension content script so the whole team gets the tags automatically without touching DevTools.

